# CI executes from `main` — commit and push to deploy

GitHub Actions and Jenkins load their pipeline definitions from the `main`
branch and auto-deploy from there. Edits sitting on a feature branch or in the
working tree have **no effect** — the runners never see them.

## Rule

When you change a GHA workflow or a Jenkins pipeline, you must land it on
`main` for it to take effect:

- Commit **all files related to the change together** (workflow/`*.jenkins`
  plus the `pipeline/*.sh`, tfvars references, and any config it drives).
- Push to `main`. Only then will GitHub Actions / Jenkins pick up and
  auto-deploy the change.
- Do **not** create commits/pushes automatically — only when the user asks
  (see git safety rules). But always **remind the user** that the change must
  reach `main` before it will run.

## Scope

- GitHub Actions: `.github/workflows/**`
- Jenkins: `**/pipeline/*.jenkins` and the `**/pipeline/*.sh` they call

## Why

Jenkins jobs (SCM-driven) and GitHub Actions both check out `main`; there is no
PR-preview or branch-based deploy path in this homelab. A change is "done" only
once it is on `main`.
